{
  "answer": "**Fichte's strongest line on this appears in his 1793 pamphlet *Reclaiming Freedom of Thought from the Princes of Europe*.** There, he rebuts censors who claim to permit thinking while restricting speech: \"yes, you permit us to think, since **you cannot prevent it**; but you forbid us to communicate our thoughts\".[^1] He frames this as an inalienable right tied to personhood—\"the prerogative of humanity\"—that no prince can legitimately seize, as humans cannot alienate their freedom to think any more than their conscience.[^2]\n\nNo work titled *Slokantara* (nor matching passages on \"bad thinking\" and the tongue in a gnomic or aphoristic style) exists in the Falsafa corpus of 37 works. Searches across English translations for relevant phrasing, authors, genres (e.g., poetry, Indic), and concepts returned no results. Without the text, I cannot pull a line or assess agreement on thinking's purpose (e.g., Fichte sees it as self-assertion and moral preparation, unbound by princes).\n\n[^1]: Johann Gottlieb Fichte, *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens*, [Chapter 2/translation/#p-b0279a](https://falsafa.corpus/book-denkfreiheit/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/02/translation/#p-b0279a).\n[^2]: Johann Gottlieb Fichte, *Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit von den Fürsten Europens*, [Chapter 2/translation/#p-e62dae](https://falsafa.corpus/book-denkfreiheit/johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde/02/translation/#p-e62dae).",
